---
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";
---

<DocsLayout title="Deployment">
  <h1>Deployment</h1>

  <p>Deploy your AI Stack to production using Docker or Kubernetes.</p>

  <div class="bg-yellow-500/10 border-l-4 border-yellow-500 p-4 mb-8">
    <p class="text-yellow-200 m-0">
      <strong>Warning:</strong> Never commit <code>.env</code> files to git. Use environment
      variables in your deployment platform.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Option 1: Docker Compose (VPS)</h2>
  <p>
    The simplest way to deploy is using Docker Compose on a single server (e.g.,
    EC2, DigitalOcean Droplet).
  </p>
  <pre
    class="bg-slate-900 p-4 rounded-lg overflow-x-auto border border-slate-800"><code class="text-slate-300"># 1. Clone repo
git clone https://github.com/your/repo.git
cd repo

# 2. Set env vars
cp .env.example .env

# 3. Build & Run
docker-compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml up -d --build</code></pre>

  <h2>Option 2: Cloud PaaS (Railway/Render)</h2>
  <p>Deploy services individually:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Backend</strong>: Deploy <code>apps/backend/Dockerfile</code>.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Frontend</strong>: Deploy <code>apps/frontend</code> (Next.js presets).
    </li>
    <li><strong>Database</strong>: Provision Managed Postgres & Redis.</li>
    <li><strong>Vector DB</strong>: Use Qdrant Cloud or Weaviate Cloud.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Option 3: Kubernetes</h2>
  <p>
    See the <a href="/docs/kubernetes">Kubernetes Deployment Guide</a> for detailed
    manifests.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
